@{U}2  Installation                                               TeraDesk@{u}  
  
The Tera Desktop should be installed as follows:  
  
1. Create  a  folder called e.g. DESKTOP or TERADESK anywhere on your  
floppy or hard disk (or in a RAM disk).  
  
2. Copy into this folder the files:  
  
       DESKTOP.PRG  (if  you  intend  to use multitasking) or   
       DESKTOS.PRG (if you  will  work  in  Single-TOS  only)    
       DESKTOP.RSC    
       ICONS.RSC  and/or  
       CICONS.PRG (if your AES can support colour icons)   
  
Note  that  DESKTOP.PRG  will  work in single-TOS as well; DESKTOS.PRG  
just  saves  a  few  kilobytes of memory by removing code which is not  
relevant in Single-TOS environment.   
  
3. If  you  use  ST-GUIDE,  copy  TERADESK.HYP and TERADESK.REF to the  
folder where your other HYP files are.  
  
4.  If  you  need  to convert TeraDesk V2.* configuration files to the  
new  format  of  TeraDesk  V3, you need to copy also CFG2INF.PRG; This  
utility  is basically a hacked compilation of the Tera Desktop itself,  
with  the  capability  to  read  only the old file format and to write  
only   the   new  format-  hence  an  inappropriately  large  size  of  
CFG2INF.PRG;  use  it  only to convert your old *.CFG files (use first  
Load Settings...  then  Save Settings as...), and  then promptly  dump  
it  to the trash bin. Note that CFG2INF.PRG uses the resource files of  
TeraDesk  V3.00,  so  do not attempt to put CFG2INF.PRG in a directory  
containing  any  other version of DESKTOP.RSC. See Configuration files  
for more details.  
  
Note  that  CFG2INF.PRG  utility  will be supported by the source code  
only in TeraDesk Version 3.00.  
  
Tera Desktop can now be started in the usual way by double clicking on   
its name.  
  
If  you  have TOS version 1.04 (also known as TOS 1.4) or greater, you  
can  set  it up so that Tera Desktop is started automatically when you  
boot. To do this:  
  
5. In the TOS built-in desktop, select the file DESKTOP.PRG by single   
clicking on it.  
  
6. Select 'Install application' from the Options menu.  
  
7. Change to boot status from 'Normal' to 'Auto'  
  
8. Click on 'Install'  
  
9. Save the desktop configuration  
  
If  you  have  TOS  version 1.0 or 1.02 you must use a program such as  
STARTGEM to run DESKTOP from an AUTO folder.  
  
If  you  use  Atari  AES  4.1,  you  can  put  something similar to the  
following directive into your GEM.CNF file:  
  
  
     shell= path\to\TeraDesk\desktop.prg  
  
Then,  the  built-in  desktop of AES 4.1 will not be loaded at startup  
and  TeraDesk  will  run  as  the  desktop  instead. Beside being more  
elegant,  this  also  saves  some  memory  (steps 5 to 9 above are not  
needed if you define TeraDesk as shell).  
   
If  you  use  MagiC,  TeraDesk  should be specified as a shell via the  
#_SHL  directive in MAGX.INF; a more adventurous user can also attempt  
to   edit  MAGIC.RAM  with  a  hex  editor,  and  -carefully-  replace  
instances  of  "MAGXDESK.APP"  with  "TERADESK.PRG",  with  a possible  
change  of path, taking care not to exceed original path length. Then,  
in   a   case  of  a  major  crash,  TeraDesk  should  be  reactivated  
automatically, not MAGXDESK.APP.  
  
Geneva  4  declares  itself  as  capable  of  handling  colour  icons.  
However,  this  doesn't  seem  to  work  with  TeraDesk. In this case,  
CICONS.RSC  file  should  be  removed,  and TeraDesk will fall back to  
monochrome icons.  
  
@endnode  
  
  
