@image udo_fo.img 4  
      Menus and Dialogues  
@image udo_fo.img 7  
         Menu title: File  
  
@{U}4.2.1  Open...                                                TeraDesk@{u}  
  
With  this  item,  a selected object can be opened. The meaning of the  
term depends on the type of the selected object.  
  
If  the  object  is  a  disk volume or a folder, a directory window is  
opened on that object  
  
If  the  object  is  a  file, and that filetype has been assigned as a  
document  type  to an application, that application is started and the  
selected file is opened.  
  
If the object is a file which has not been assigned to an application,   
an alert with the Show/Edit/Cancel options is displayed.  
  
- Selecting Show opens a Text window with the selected file  
- Selecting Edit calls an installed editor (if it has been installed)  
  to open the file.  
    
If the object  is an executable file (program), it is started.  
  
If no objects are selected, a dialogue opens in which the full path and   
name of the object can be entered in the '@{"scrolled editable field" link "Scrolled text fields"}'. TeraDesk tries to divine the type of the   
item  so  specified:  a  file,  a folder, an application or a document  
assigned  to an application, and acts accordingly, as presented above.  
If  an  application  is  specified  in  the  dialog,  its  name can be  
followed by a command tail (after a blank character).  
  
  
@endnode  
  
  
@node "Object info..."  
@toc "Menu title: File"  
@image udo_fo.img 1  
   Contents  
@image udo_fo.img 4  
      Menus and Dialogues  
@image udo_fo.img 7  
         Menu title: File  
  
@{U}4.2.2  Object info...                                         TeraDesk@{u}  
  
When  this  item  is selected, Tera Desktop displays information about  
an object (or objects) you have previously selected:  
  
1. If the selected object is a file, its name, path, the time and date   
it  was last modified and the number of bytes in it will be displayed.  
The  name  of  the  file, access date and time can be changed. You can  
also   set/unset   the  Write  Protect,  Archive,  Hidden  and  System  
attributes   of  the  file.  If  the  file  is  write-protected,  this  
attribute  must be reset before attempting to change other information  
related  to  that  file.  If time and date fields are cleared, current  
time and date will be set for the file.  
  
2. If the selected object is a folder, its name, the time  and date of   
it  creation,  the number of files and folders in it and the number of  
bytes  used  will  be  displayed.  Folder  attributes  (Write Protect,  
Archive,  Hidden and System) are also displayed, although they are not  
settable  in TOS (they can be set e.g. on a floppy disk manipulated in  
Windows  on  a  PC).  With TOS version 1.04 and above, the folder name  
can be changed.  
  
3. If  the  selected  object  is  a disk volume, the drive letter, the  
volume  label,  the  number  of files and folders on it, the number of  
used  and  available bytes, the total free space on it and the cluster  
size  will be displayed. If the disk is empty, it is possible that the  
total  space  and  the  free space will be different; this is due to a  
bug in TOS.  
  
  
4.  If  no  object  has  been  selected,  Tera  Desktop  will  display 
information  on the disk volume of the top directory window, if any is 
open. 
  
  
It  is  possible  to  select more than one object before invoking this  
menu  item;  content  of  the  dialog  box  will change to show fields  
appropriate for the selected item types in turn.  
  
Selecting  'All' will cause setting of file attributes and/or date and  
time   on   all  selected  file  items.  Selecting  this  button  when  
information  on  a  folder is shown, will cause setting of attributes,  
date  and  time on all files in the folder and its subfolders, but the  
data  for  the folders themselves will not be affected. This action is  
confirmed  by  the  appearance  of  a  dialogue  in which the user can  
select  whether  only file attributes should be set, or time and date,  
or both.  
  
Selecting  'OK'  will  cause  setting  of  all  displayed data for the  
currently displayed item.  
  
Selecting  'Skip'  will  cancel  all  changes  made  for the currently  
displayed item and show the next selected item.  
  
Selecting  'Abort'  will  cause closing the dialog and cancellation of  
all changes.  
  
See also: Scrolled text fields, Search...  
  
@endnode  
  
@node "Compare files"  
@toc "Menu title: File"  
@image udo_fo.img 1  
   Contents  
@image udo_fo.img 4  
      Menus and Dialogues  
@image udo_fo.img 7  
         Menu title: File  
  
@{U}4.2.3   Compare files                                         TeraDesk@{u}  
  
Tera  Desktop  has  the capability to compare contents of files. It is  
enabled  only  when a selection of exactly one or two files is made in  
directory  window(s).  If only one file is selected, the file selector  
is  invoked to point to the second file. When a difference between the  
contents  of  the  two  files  is  detected, an alert box is displayed  
showing  the contents of both files near the detected difference. Note  
that  some  characters have to be replaced by substitutions (the [Del]  
character,   usually  represented  by  a  small  triangle,  is  used),  
because, if displayed, they would corrupt the display.  
  
File   comparison   function   tries  to  use  some  intelligence  and  
resynchronize  further  search  in  the  files  after  a difference is  
found.  Width of the resynchronization window is currently fixed to 10  
characters.  This should be enough to continue comparison of a pair of  
files  after a difference of only several bytes is encountered, e.g. a  
single  different  word,  or  a single blank line in one of the files.  
This  function  completely reads both files into memory, and may be of  
limited use on machines with minimum RAM.  
  
@endnode  
  
@node "Search..."  
@toc "Menu title: File"  
@image udo_fo.img 1  
   Contents  
@image udo_fo.img 4  
      Menus and Dialogues  
@image udo_fo.img 7  
         Menu title: File  
  
@{U}4.2.4   Search...                                             TeraDesk@{u}  
  
When  this  item  is selected, a dialogue appears in which the pattern  
to  be  searched  in  the  selected  folders  and / or disk volumes is  
specified.  
  
File/folder name or name mask must always be specified.  
  
Date and size limits are optional; if left blank, TeraDesk will ignore   
them.  
  
String  to  be  searched  for is optional. If left blank, Tera Desktop  
will  only  search for files and folders matching the pattern mask. If  
any  string is specified, Tera Desktop will search for it in the files  
witch match the pattern mask.  
  
If  a  match  is  found  the Object info... dialogue is opened showing  
specification  of  the  found  object.  If  a  search  string has been  
entered,  file contents surrounding the found string are displayed; to  
save  space,  the  string  itself is replaced by [...] so that more of  
the  text  preceding  and  following the string can be displayed. Note  
that  some  characters  which  would  corrupt  the  formatting  of the  
displayed  text  are  replaced by a substitute- the [Delete] character  
which is in most fonts represented by a small triangle.  
  
Note  that  each  file  searched  for strings is first completely read  
into  memory. Therefore, searching in large files may not be possible,  
depending  on  the  amount  of  free memory. If a search string is not  
specified,  search  will  involve  only file and folder names, without  
actually reading any files.  
  
@endnode  
  
