@{U}4.5 Keyboard shortcuts                                        TeraDesk@{u}  
  
Beside  being  selected  by  a  mouse,  menu  items  can  be set to be 
selected  by  pressing  a  key  or  a  key combination. These keyboard 
shortcuts are set in the Desk preferences... dialogue. 
  
Likewise,  most  buttons  in  dialogue boxes can also be selected by a 
key:  Press  and  hold  down [Alternate] and then press the key of the 
character in the button that is underlined. 
  
Boxes  with  arrows  can  be  selected  by  holding down [Control] and 
pressing the corresponding cursor (arrow) key on the keyboard. 
  
Directory  windows  on  disk  volume root directories can be opened by 
pressing  the  [Alternate][?]  key  combination  ('?' representing the 
drive   letter,   i.e.   A   to   P   or   A   to   Z).  Pressing  the 
[Alternate][Shift][?]  combination will open the root directory of the 
specified disk volume in the existing top window. 
  
If  [Shift][Help] key combination is pressed, TeraDesk will attempt to 
call   ST-Guide   if  it  is  installed,  to  open  TERADESK.HYP  file 
containing  this user manual. Note that, for the moment, the .HYP file 
has  -NOT-  been  completely  updated  to  reflect all changes and new 
features in TeraDesk Version 3. 
  
Pressing  [Help]  key  invokes a Help dialogue with brief explanations 
of basic keyboard commands. 
  
@endnode  
  
@node "The listbox dialogue"  
@image udo_fo.img 1  
   Contents  
@image udo_fo.img 4  
      Menus and Dialogues  
  
@{U}4.6 The listbox dialogue                                      TeraDesk@{u}  
  
TeraDesk   maintains  lists  of  filetype  masks,  window icon  types, 
executable   program   types,   installed  applications  and  assigned 
filetypes.  The same type of dialogue, containing a scrollable listbox 
and  five  edit buttons is used to maintain all these lists, but it is 
invoked through diverse menu items, depending on the use: 
 
  
Set mask...   to  maintain  a  list  of  predefined filetype masks for 
TeraDesk's Directory windows 
  
Set applications... to maintain a list of installed applications   
  
Set program types... to maintain a list of  executable file types  
  
Set window icons... to maintain lists of icons assigned to certain   
filenames or filetypes or folder names  
  
Set document types... to maintain lists of  document types assigned to 
applications.  This  is  a  second-level  dialogue and it is activated 
from the Set applications... dialogue. 
  
Listbox content is manipulated by five buttons (Add, Edit, delete,   
Up-arrow and Down-arrow).   
  
Add:  opens  a second-level dialogue to fill-in data for an item which 
will be added to the list at the highlighted position. 
  
Edit:  opens  a  second-level  dialogue  to  edit  data for an already 
existing item. 
  
Delete: deletes the highlighted item in the list.  
  
Up-arrow: moves an item up in the list  
  
Down-arrow: moves an item down the list  
  
The  purpose  of  the  last  two  buttons is to enable editing of item 
order.  TeraDesk searches all lists starting from the beginning, until 
the   first   match  is  found.  It  may  be  desirable  to   put  the 
often-needed items nearer to the top of the list. 
  
Items  can  be added (or edited) in all of TeraDesk's lists, except in 
the  lists  of  document-types  assigned  to applications, in the same 
way:  either  you  can  manually enter all data related to an item, or 
you  can  select  an item in a directory window or on the desktop, and 
then  open  the  desired  dialog  to modify the default settings which 
TeraDesk   assigned  for  an  item  added  to  a  list  in  this  way. 
Document-types  asigned  to  applications can be edited only manually, 
being  in the second-level of dialog (i.e. they can not be selected in 
a window). 
  
@endnode  
  
  
